{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491435"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/939"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.23,0.1,0.29,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/939"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"579"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44929"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful swelling of his left ear that appeared after he was involved in a scuffle several hours earlier. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm diameter tender bruise on the anterior aspect of the pinna. There is no drainage from the auditory canal, nor any impediment to his hearing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation and review in 24 hours","Compression dressing and review in 24 hours","Needle aspiration","Incision, drainage and bolster dressing","Incision, drainage and primary wound closure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an auricular haematoma, which requires prompt treatment to prevent complications. The most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision, drainage and bolster dressing\u003C/strong\u003E. The auricular cartilage receives its blood supply from the overlying perichondrium and if a haematoma is allowed to accumulate between these two structures, the underlying cartilage is at risk of ischaemia and necrosis. If this occurs there may be overgrowth of fibrocartilage and a subsequent deformity, often referred to as \u0027cauliflower ear.\u0027 Thus, prompt action and drainage of these haematomas is advised. Pressure should then be applied to close the potential dead space where the haematoma had formed. This can be done by using mattress sutures to hold a bolster dressing in position. This approach ensures complete drainage of the haematoma and prevents its reaccumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not appropriate for auricular haematomas. The auricular cartilage receives its blood supply from the overlying perichondrium. If a haematoma is allowed to accumulate between these two structures, the underlying cartilage is at risk of ischaemia and necrosis. This can lead to overgrowth of fibrocartilage and subsequent deformity, often referred to as \u0027cauliflower ear\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompression dressing\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient to treat an established auricular haematoma. While compression can help prevent reaccumulation after drainage, it does not address the existing fluid collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E, while less invasive, is generally not recommended as the sole treatment for auricular haematomas. It often results in incomplete drainage and a high rate of reaccumulation. Additionally, it does not allow for the placement of a bolster dressing to prevent reaccumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision, drainage and primary wound closure\u003C/strong\u003E without a bolster dressing is not ideal. While this would drain the haematoma, it doesn\u0027t provide the necessary compression to prevent reaccumulation and ensure proper healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter incision and drainage, a bolster dressing should be applied using mattress sutures to hold it in position. This closes the potential dead space where the haematoma had formed and applies pressure to prevent reaccumulation. The patient should be followed up closely to ensure proper healing and to remove the bolster dressing after an appropriate period, typically 5-7 days.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Auricular haematomas must be drained promptly to prevent cartilage necrosis and subsequent \u0027cauliflower ear\u0027 deformity.","Incision, drainage, and bolster dressing is the preferred treatment for auricular haematomas to ensure complete drainage and prevent reaccumulation."],"references":["Henry M, Hern HG. Traumatic Injuries of the Ear, Nose and Throat. Emergency Med Clin N Am 2019; 37:131-36."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40856"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T19:45:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T08:19:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"939"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/579"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Auricular haematoma","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T14:58:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1984"},"attributes":{"emoji":"